register.description: CALC3 mode select register

bitfield.description: Enable Left block Intra-Mode change in Constraint-Intra-Predication (Only in Encode) [1] : mode-change enable [0] : mode-change diable
Enc or Dec mode flag [0] : Dec [1] : Enc Note that a part of codecs is supported only for dec. RealVideo, VP6/7, H.263 AnnexI mode are supported only for dec. Enc mode is reserved for them.
CALC5_EN bit will be cleared and interupt is generated Stop Calc @ [0] : Pipe-Down [1] : Slice End [2] : End-of-Row [3] : MB-Done

CBPControl #0 enable flag for Inter Block [0] : disable [1] : enable It is effective for enc only. For an 8x8 block (w/o DcTransform) and its block of inter, if all the non-zero coeffs among quantized 64 coeffs are less than one in abs domain and the number of the ones coeffs <= threshold_0, this corresponded CBP sets to zero, where threshold_0 = CALC_CBPCNT0_INTER_THR + 1. Its threshold of threshold_0 can be set in the CBP_CTRL0_INTER_TH register. Note that the abs one coefficients does not turn to zero in the residual data, the CBP is only controlled to zero.

CBPControl #0 enable flag for Luma DC Trans mode [0] : disable [1] : enable It is effective for enc and DC transform used in Luma 16x16 block. When DcTransform is effective for Luma and this flag = 1, if all the non-zero coeffs among quantized 60 AC coeffs (w/o 4DC coeffs) in an 8x8 luma block are one in abs domain and the number of ones coeffs is less than threshold_1, this corresponded CBP sets to zero, where threshold_1 = CALC_CBPCNT0_LUMA_DCTRANS_THR + 1. Its threshold of threshold_1 can be set in the CBP_CTRL0_LUMA_I16x16_TH register. Note that the abs one coefficients are not turns to zero in the residual data, the CBP is only controlled to zero.

CBPControl #0 enable flag for Chroma DC Trans mode [0] : disable [1] : enable It is effective for enc and DC transform used in Cb and Cr blocks. When DcTransform is effective for Cb/Cr and this flag = 1, if all the non-zero coeffs among quantized 60 AC coeffs (w/o 4DC coeffs) in the 8x8 block are one in abs domain and the number of ones coeffs is less than threshold_2, this corresponded CBP sets to zero, , where threshold_2 = CALC_CBPCNT0_CHRO_DCTRANS_THR + 1. Its threshold of threshold_2 is set in the CALC_CBPCNT0_CHRO_DCTRANS_THR register. Note that the abs one coefficients are not turns to zero in the residual data, the CBP is only controlled to zero.
# of abs ones coeffs threshold for CBP_CTRL0_LUMA_INTER_EN It is effective for CBP_CTRL0_LUMA_INTER_EN = 1 [0] : threshold_0 = 1 [1] : threshold_0 = 2
# of abs ones coeffs threshold for CBP_CTRL0_LUMA_I16x16_EN It is effective for CBP_CTRL0_LUMA_I16x16_EN = 1 [0] : threshold_1 = 1 [1] : threshold_1 = 2
# of abs ones coeffs threshold for CBP_CTRL0_CHROMA_EN It is effective for CBP_CTRL0_CHRO_EN = 1 [0] : threshold_2 = 1 [1] : threshold_2 = 2
Enable SVC [0] : Disable SVC [1] : Enable SVC
[0] H.264 [other] : Reserved

register.description: Clock management configuration

bitfield.description: Software reset Read0: Reset done, no pending action Read1: Reset (software or other) on going Write0: No action Write1: Initiate software reset
Sensitivity to emulation (debug) suspend input signal. 0: IP module is sensitive to emulation suspend 1: IP module is not sensitive to emulation suspend

Configuration of the local target state management mode. By definition, target can handle read/write transaction as long as it is out of IDLE state. 0: Force-idle mode: local target's idle state follows (acknowledges) the system's idle requests unconditionally, i.e. regardless of the IP module's internal requirements. Backup mode, for debug only. 1: No-idle mode: local target never enters idle state. Backup mode, for debug only. 2: Smart-idle mode: local target's idle state eventually follows (acknowledges) the system's idle requests, depending on the IP module's internal requirements. IP module shall not generate (IRQ- or DMA-request-related) wakeup events. 3: Smart-idle wakeup-capable mode: local target's idle state eventually follows (acknowledges) the system's idle requests, depending on the IP module's internal requirements. IP module may generate (IRQ- or DMA-request-related) wakeup events when in idle state. Mode is only relevant if the appropriate IP module "swakeup" output(s) is (are) implemented.

register.description: Debug Control register is used by debug software to control all of the basic debug functions.

bitfield.description: Global debug run control The bit will be read as being set upon entry to HALTED state due to halted state being entered because of SWBP, HWBP, HWWP, EMU0 / 1 trigger or manual halt requested through this control. • Writing ‘1’ when read ‘0’ shall cause a halt on the next possible halt boundary. • Writing ‘0’ when read ‘1’ returns the system to the natural execution state. • Reading ‘1’ means that the halted state has been reached. • Reading ‘0’ means that the target is in its natural execution state. NOTE: 1. The natural execution state means the FSM state entered prior to last entry into Halted state. 2. This would be the last application requested FSM state unless the DBG_SYS_EXE_REQ control was used to change it.

Debug Restart Status bit • Reading ‘1’ means HWA Core exited halted state (at least temporarily). • Reading ‘0’ means HWA Core did not exit halted state. • Writing ‘1’ shall clear the bit if set. There is no restriction on when it can be cleared. • Writing ‘0’ shall have no effect.

Single Step Execution enable When this bit is set, the accelerator core shall be halted upon execution of a single instruction. This is after the accelerator core has left the halted state by clearing the DBG_HALT control bit.
• Writing ‘1’ enables halting when the next instruction following exit from halted state is executed. • Writing ‘0’ disables halts via single step.
NOTE: 1. When the accelerator core enters its natural execution state, it may or may not execute an instruction and re-enter HALTED state.
EMU0 input trigger enable • Writing ‘1’ enables halting on the falling edge of the EMU0 input • Writing ‘0’ disables halts via EMU0 input
The execution status of the module • Set to ‘1’ when halted due to debug event • Set to ‘0’ when execution resumes
Execution halted due to single step completion • Set to ‘1’ when the single step completes • Set to ‘0’ when execution resumes
Execution halted due to register update of DBG_HALT • Set to ‘1’ when halt due to DBG_HALT update completes • Set to ‘0’ when execution resumes
Execution halted due to trigger in on EMU0 input • Set to ‘1’ when halt due to EMU0 input completes • Set to ‘0’ when execution resumes
Statues of EMU0 input. This bit indicates the current value of the EMU0 input

EMU0 output control. The cross trigger output control. This values in this field determine the behavior of the outputs generated on EMU0.
NOTE: The effect of setting ‘1’ is ignored if the HWA Core is currently in HALTED state until the HWA core exits and re-enters HALTED state.
0 : No output. Input only 1 : Pulse on halt. If this bit is set when halted then no effect until the HWA re-enters halted state. 2 : Pulse when any HWBP triggers 3 : Pulse when any HWWP triggers 4 : Drive pin high 5 : Drive pin low 6-15 : Reserved

This bit enables the halts on watchpoint or hardware breakpoint trigger events. • Writing ‘1’ enables halting on any hardware breakpoint or watchpoint trigger  Each breakpoint or watchpoint resource also has a local enable • Writing ‘0’ disables halts via hardware breakpoints or watchpoints
Execution halted due to trigger from HWBP or WP. • Set to ‘1’ halt due to breakpoint or watchpoint completes • Set to ‘0’ when execution resumes
